<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
In our phylogeny Mexican sequences of specimens Herrera 120 and 121 clustered (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Phylogenetic relationships within Cantharellus species inferred from the combined nLSU (large subunit of the ribosome) and tef- 1 α (transcription elongation factor 1 - alpha) sequences, by maximum likelihood method and Bayesian inference. The new species are indicated in bold letters. Bootstrap scores (only values ≥ 70) and Bayesian Posterior Probabilities (only values ≥ 0.90) are indicated above branches." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.80.61443.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545049" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">1</figureCitation>
) with high values of Bootstrap and Bayesian posterior probabilities (96/0.99) with a sequence of the type specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Feib. &amp; Cibula, Mycologia 88: 299" authorityYear="1996" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus tabernensis" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="tabernensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus tabernensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from U.S.A., produced by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-013-0272-3" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="101 - 121" refId="B11" refString="Buyck, B, Kauff, F, Eyssartier, G, Couloux, A, Hofstetter, V, 2014. A multilocus phylogeny for worldwide Cantharellus (Cantharellales, Agaricomycetidae). Fungal Diversity 64 (1): 101 - 121, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-013-0272-3" title="A multilocus phylogeny for worldwide Cantharellus (Cantharellales, Agaricomycetidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-013-0272-3" volume="64" year="2014">Buyck et al. (2014)</bibRefCitation>
. The morphological description provided above includes both mentioned specimens, and in fact, in the most relevant characters, those specimens agree with the species. It should be mentioned, however, that the following features recorded in the description provided by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" author="Feibelman, TP" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="295 - 301" refId="B20" refString="Feibelman, TP, Bennett, JW, Cibula, WG, 1996. Cantharellus tabernensis: A new species from the Southeastern United States. Mycologia 88 (2): 295 - 301, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" title="Cantharellus tabernensis: A new species from the Southeastern United States." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" volume="88" year="1996">Feibelman et al. (1996)</bibRefCitation>
were not observed in the Mexican material: pileus mat felted overall, often umbilicate, sometimes perforated, basidia 4-5-6 -spored and dark plasmatic pigment confined to clavate terminal cells of the surface hyphae at disc.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
The record presented here of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. tabernensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="tabernensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. tabernensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in its turn provides additional information on the species distribution. It is known from the mixed pine and hardwood forests, usually near 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus elliotii" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="elliotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Pinus elliotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Engelm., at the Gulf coastal plain in Texas, Mississippi, and Louisiana states in USA (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" author="Feibelman, TP" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="295 - 301" refId="B20" refString="Feibelman, TP, Bennett, JW, Cibula, WG, 1996. Cantharellus tabernensis: A new species from the Southeastern United States. Mycologia 88 (2): 295 - 301, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" title="Cantharellus tabernensis: A new species from the Southeastern United States." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.1996.12026655" volume="88" year="1996">Feibelman et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
), and now 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. tabernensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="tabernensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. tabernensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known also in the tropical 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest from Veracruz, in the coastal plain of Veracruz state in the Gulf of Mexico.
</paragraph>
